<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
     F. FAQ ACCORDION
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="pcm-faq" aria-label="Frequently asked questions">
  <div class="pcm-faq-inner">
    <h2 class="pcm-section-title">Common questions</h2>
    <div class="pcm-faq-list">

      <div class="pcm-faq-item">
        <button class="pcm-faq-question" aria-expanded="false" type="button">
          <span>Does the mat work on its own?</span>
          <svg class="pcm-faq-icon" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
            <path d="M3 6l5 5 5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="pcm-faq-answer" hidden>
          <p>No. A lick mat is not a treatment &mdash; it is a tool. Used as part of the PAXA Solo Protocol or any structured desensitisation programme, it creates a reliable physiological anchor during the critical cortisol window. Without the protocol, it is simply enrichment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="pcm-faq-item">
        <button class="pcm-faq-question" aria-expanded="false" type="button">
          <span>Which variant should I choose?</span>
          <svg class="pcm-faq-icon" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
            <path d="M3 6l5 5 5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="pcm-faq-answer" hidden>
          <p>The Protocol Pair (Milk White + Sky Blue) is the standard two-mat setup used across all four phases of the protocol. The Regulation Pair suits sensitive or reactive dogs in early foundation work. The Anchor Pair is designed for threshold management in Phase 3 &mdash; the visual contrast accelerates conditioned response.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="pcm-faq-item">
        <button class="pcm-faq-question" aria-expanded="false" type="button">
          <span>Is it safe for all dogs?</span>
          <svg class="pcm-faq-icon" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
            <path d="M3 6l5 5 5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="pcm-faq-answer" hidden>
          <p>Yes. The mats are food-grade silicone, BPA-free confirmed. The suction cup base prevents movement during sessions, which is important for maintaining the environmental cue. Always supervise the first few sessions to ensure your dog engages correctly.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="pcm-faq-item">
        <button class="pcm-faq-question" aria-expanded="false" type="button">
          <span>How do I clean it?</span>
          <svg class="pcm-faq-icon" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
            <path d="M3 6l5 5 5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="pcm-faq-answer" hidden>
          <p>Dishwasher safe &mdash; top rack only. Alternatively, rinse with warm water and a soft brush. Do not use abrasive cleaners or solvents. The silicone is non-porous and resists bacterial build-up between sessions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="pcm-faq-item">
        <button class="pcm-faq-question" aria-expanded="false" type="button">
          <span>What if my dog isn&rsquo;t interested?</span>
          <svg class="pcm-faq-icon" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
            <path d="M3 6l5 5 5-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="pcm-faq-answer" hidden>
          <p>This is common in the first 1&ndash;2 sessions. Start with a high-value paste (peanut butter, soft cheese, meat paste). Smear it into all four texture zones. Freeze the mat overnight for longer engagement. Most dogs are fully engaged within 3 sessions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

